ena. Fascists within the GMD deployed modernist aesthetics in their literature and art while justifying their anti-Communist violence with nativist discourse. Showing how the GMD's fascist factions popularized a virulently nationalist rhetoric that linked Confucianism with a specific path of industrial development, Clinton sheds new light on the complex dynamics of Chinese nationalism and modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aFascismxChina. 0aFascismzChina. 0aFascism. 0aNationalismxChina. 0aNationalismzChina. 0aNationalism. 0aPolitics and culturexChina. 0aPolitics and culturezChina. 0aPolitics and culture. 0aPolitics and government. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373032zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822373032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822373032.jpg  a978-3-11-069634-9  DUK eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles